Setting up Jupyter Notebook on Google Cloud

John Manalastas | 07 Oct 2019

Why Setup a VM Instance¶

For most aspiring data scientists on a budget, you will quickly realized that your current rig is not up to par with the projects you might want to tackle. I expirenced this with my personal laptop, where both memory or computing power are not able to do the data crunch.

A solution to this problem is to create virtual machine (vm). In my case, I used the Google Cloud Platform as opposed to AWS EC2. The GCP is developed enough that it is competitive against AWS.

This tutorial will include the following:

  • Create an instance on Google Computer Engine (GCE)
  • Customize both firewall and ip address for easy use
  • Install Jupyter notebook and popular libraries related to data science
  • Run Jupyter notebook accessible online

Advantages of cloud computing over local machine¶

There are two main advantages when working with cloud:

  • First, it is scalable. You are able to tailor your machine's RAM, CPU, GPU and memory for current use and add more power to each as needed.
  • Second, it is easily shared. Yes, we have github for that, but the cloud can be instantly accessed from any machine at anytime, as long as the vm instance is open.

Getting Started¶

Create an Account and Project:¶

To use the GCP you need to create a Google account. At the time of this writing a new account with a new debit/credit card is given a 12 months or 300 usd free trial of the platform, whichever runs out first. The 300 usd credit is enough to get you started and if you need more time with the vm, you are always free to register another card.

To create your GCP account go to link(http://cloud.google.com) and click on the "try it free" button. You'll be asked to login with your google account and billing info. Once that is done go to link(http://console.cloud.googl.com)

Step 2: Create a new project¶

Click on the three dots shown in the image below and then click on the + sign to create a new project.

Step 3: Create a VM instance¶

Click on the three lines on the upper left corner, then on the COMPUTER option, click on 'Compute Engine'

Customize your machine.

Now click on 'Create new instance.' Name your instance, select zone as ‘ us-west1-b’. Choose your ‘machine type.’

Select your boot disk as "Ubuton 16.04 LTS." Under the firewall options select both 'http' and 'https.' Then, choose the disk tab and untick ‘ Delete boot disk when instance is deleted’.

If you click on ‘customize’, you will be able to find options for using GPUs. You can choose between 4 different NVIDIA Tesla GPUs.¶

Firewall Settings:¶

Now click on "Create" and your insance is ready!¶

Your new VM instance should look something like this. Note down the External IP. This is used to access the Jupyter Notebook.

IMPORTANT : Don't do it now, but always stop your VM instance after each use by clicking on the three dots on the image below and selecting stop. Otherwise the VM will drain your $300 credit¶

Step 4: Make external IP address as static¶

By default, the external IP address is dynamic and we need to make it static to make our life easier. Click on the three horizontal lines on top left and then under networking, click on VPC network and then External IP addresses.

Change the type from Ephemeral to Static.¶

Step 5: Change the Firewall setting¶

Now, click on the 'Firewall rules' throuhgh the VPC network.¶

Click on 'Create Firewall Rules' and refer to the image below:¶

Under protocols and ports you can choose any port. I have chosen tep:5000 as my port number. Now click on the save button.¶

Step 6: Start your VM instance¶

Now start your VM instance. When you see the green tick click on SSH. This will open a command window and now you are inside the VM.

Step 7: Install Jupyter notebook and other packages¶

In your SSH terminal, enter:

wget https://repo.anaconda.com/archive/Anaconda3-2019.07-Windows-x86_64.exe¶

and follow the on-screen instructions. The defaults usually work fine, but answer yes to the last question about prepending the install location to PATH:

To make use of Anaconda right away, source your bashrc:

"source~/.bashrc" or a shorter version is: ".~/.bashrc"

Step 8: Set up the VM server¶

Open up a SSH session to your VM. Check if you have a Jupyter configuration file:

Type: ls ~/.jupyter/jupyter_notebook_config.py

If it doesn't exist, create one:

Type: jupyter notebook --generate-config

We’re going to add a few lines to your Jupyter configuration file; the file is plain text so, you can do this via your favorite editor (e.g., vim, emacs). Make sure you replace the port number with the one you allowed firewall access to in step 5.

Type:
c = get_config()
c.NotebookApp.ip = '*'
c.NotebookApp.open_browser = False
c.NotebookApp.port = "Port Number"

It should look something like this:

Step 9: Launching Jupyter Notebook¶

To run the jupyter notebook, just type the following command in the ssh window you are in:¶

Type: jupyter-notebook --no-browser --port="port number"

Once you run the command, it should show somtjhing like this:

Now to launch your jupyter notebook, just type the following in your browser:

Type: httP://"external Static IP Address":"portnumber"

where, external ip address is the ip address which we made static and port number is the one which we allowed firewall access to.

Congratualtions, you've created your first Jupyter notebook in a VM instance!!¶
